result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Cases heard: 14CF145, 14CF190, 13CM324, Defendant Nina I. Downey in court with attorney Peter Michael Masana.  Christine M. Genda appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court went over the rights & elements. Defendant plead no contest to counts 2&6 in 14CF145 and count 3 in 13CM324. Court found defendant guilty, entered judgment, sentence withheld in 14CF145 on ct. 2 & count 3 in 13CM324, defendant placed on 2 yrs. probation with conds: Complete AODA and comply with all treatment recommendations. Maintain full-time employment or in school full time  or be seeking employment. No contact with K.V. or M.T., $309 restitution. $443 costs on each count. In both cases, Defendant may petition Court in writing, after two years, for expunction of record, contingent upon successful completion of probation, Deferred Prosecution Agreement not having been revoked, or any alternatives to probation imposed, no new law violations and costs and restitution paid in full. Deferred Prosecution Agreement on ct. 6. Held open for compliance. Ct. 1 in 14CF145 dismissed. Court granted 1 day jail credit in 14CF145. Court read in and dismissed 14CF190.
